Unit 3
Electrochemistry





Chemical reactions can be used to produce electrical energy, conversely, electrical energy can be used to carry out chemical reactions that do not proceed spontaneously.", "fibs": ["Unit"]}
{"text": "Objectives



After studying this Unit, you will be able to







describe an electrochemical cell and differentiate between galvanic and electrolytic cells;
apply Nernst equation for calculating the emf of galvanic cell and define standard potential of the cell;
derive relation between standard potential of the cell, Gibbs energy of cell reaction and its equilibrium constant;
define resistivity (ρ), conductivity (κ) and molar conductivity (^m) of ionic solutions;
differentiate between ionic (electrolytic) and electronic conductivity;
describe the method for measurement of conductivity of electrolytic solutions and calculation of their molar conductivity;
justify the variation of conductivity and molar conductivity of solutions with change in their concentration and define (molar conductivity at zero concentration or infinite dilution);
enunciate Kohlrausch law and learn its applications;
understand quantitative aspects of electrolysis;
describe the construction of some primary and secondary batteries and fuel cells;
explain corrosion as an electrochemical process.", "fibs": ["Unit"]}
{"text": "Electrochemistry is the study of production of electricity from energy released during spontaneous chemical reactions and the use of electrical energy to bring about non-spontaneous chemical transformations.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "The subject is of importance both for theoretical and practical considerations.", "fibs": ["subject"]}
{"text": "A large number of metals, sodium hydroxide, chlorine, fluorine and many other chemicals are produced by electrochemical methods.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Batteries and fuel cells convert chemical energy into electrical energy and are used on a large scale in various instruments and devices.", "fibs": ["fuel"]}
{"text": "The reactions carried out electrochemically can be energy efficient and less polluting.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Therefore, study of electrochemistry is important for creating new technologies that are ecofriendly.", "fibs": ["study"]}
{"text": "The transmission of sensory signals through cells to brain and vice versa and communication between the cells are known to have electrochemical origin.", "fibs": ["transmission"]}
{"text": "Electrochemistry, is therefore, a very vast and interdisciplinary subject.", "fibs": ["interdisciplinary"]}
{"text": "In this Unit, we will cover only some of its important elementary aspects.", "fibs": ["Unit"]}
