{"text": "3.2 Galvanic Cells 
As mentioned earlier (Class XI, Unit 8) a galvanic cell is an electrochemical cell that converts the chemical energy of a spontaneous redox reaction into electrical energy.", "fibs": ["XI"]}
{"text": "In this device the Gibbs energy of the spontaneous redox reaction is converted into electrical work which may be used for running a motor or other electrical gadgets like heater, fan, geyser, etc.", "fibs": ["device"]}
{"text": "Daniell cell discussed earlier is one such cell in which the following redox reaction occurs.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Zn(s) + Cu2+(aq) → Zn2+ (aq) + Cu(s)
This reaction is a combination of two half reactions whose addition gives the overall cell reaction:
(i) Cu2+ + 2e– → Cu(s) (reduction half reaction)                                      (3.2)
(ii) Zn(s) → Zn2+ + 2e– (oxidation half reaction)                                      (3.3)
These reactions occur in two different portions of the Daniell cell.", "fibs": ["Cu2+(aq"]}
{"text": "The reduction half reaction occurs on the copper electrode while the oxidation half reaction occurs on the zinc electrode.", "fibs": ["reduction"]}
{"text": "These two portions of the cell are also called half-cells or redox couples.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "The copper electrode may be called the reduction half cell and the zinc electrode, the oxidation half-cell.", "fibs": ["copper"]}
{"text": "We can construct innumerable number of galvanic cells on the pattern of Daniell cell by taking combinations of different half-cells.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Each half-cell consists of a metallic electrode dipped into an electrolyte.", "fibs": ["electrode"]}
{"text": "The two half-cells are connected by a metallic wire through a voltmeter and a switch externally.", "fibs": ["wire"]}
{"text": "The electrolytes of the two half-cells are connected internally through a salt bridge as shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["salt"]}
{"text": "Sometimes, both the electrodes dip in the same electrolyte solution and in such cases we do not require a salt bridge.", "fibs": ["dip"]}
{"text": "At each electrode-electrolyte interface there is a tendency of metal ions from the solution to deposit on the metal electrode trying to make it positively charged.", "fibs": ["interface"]}
{"text": "At the same time, metal atoms of the electrode have a tendency to go into the solution as ions and leave behind the electrons at the electrode trying to make it negatively charged.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "At equilibrium, there is a separation of charges and depending on the tendencies of the two opposing reactions, the electrode may be positively or negatively charged with respect to the solution.", "fibs": ["equilibrium"]}
{"text": "A potential difference develops between the electrode and the electrolyte which is called electrode potential.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "When the concentrations of all the species involved in a half-cell is unity then the electrode potential is known as standard electrode potential.", "fibs": ["species"]}
{"text": "According to IUPAC convention, standard reduction potentials are now called standard electrode potentials.", "fibs": ["IUPAC"]}
{"text": "In a galvanic cell, the half-cell in which oxidation takes place is called anode and it has a negative potential with respect to the solution.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "The other half-cell in which reduction takes place is called cathode and it has a positive potential with respect to the solution.", "fibs": ["reduction"]}
{"text": "Thus, there exists a potential difference between the two electrodes and as soon as the switch is in the on position the electrons flow from negative electrode to positive electrode.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "The direction of current flow is opposite to that of electron flow.", "fibs": ["direction"]}
{"text": "The potential difference between the two electrodes of a galvanic cell is called the cell potential and is measured in volts.", "fibs": ["difference"]}
{"text": "The cell potential is the difference between the electrode potentials (reduction potentials) of the cathode and anode.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "It is called the cell electromotive force (emf) of the cell when no current is drawn through the cell.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "It is now an accepted convention that we keep the anode on the left and the cathode on the right while representing the galvanic cell.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "A galvanic cell is generally represented by putting a vertical line between metal and electrolyte solution and putting a double vertical line between the two electrolytes connected by a salt bridge.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Under this convention the emf of the cell is positive and is given by the potential of the half-cell on the right hand side minus the potential of the half-cell on the left hand side i.e.,
Ecell = Eright – Eleft
This is illustrated by the following example:
Cell reaction:
Cu(s) + 2Ag+(aq) → Cu2+(aq) + 2 Ag(s)                                     (3.4)
Half-cell reactions:
Cathode (reduction): 2Ag+(aq) + 2e– → 2Ag(s)                             (3.5)
Anode (oxidation): Cu(s) → Cu2+(aq) + 2e–                                  (3.6)
It can be seen that the sum of (3.5) and (3.6) leads to overall reaction (3.4) in the cell and that silver electrode acts as a cathode and copper electrode acts as an anode.", "fibs": ["convention"]}
{"text": "The cell can be represented as:
Cu(s)|Cu2+(aq) || Ag+(aq)|Ag(s)
and we have Ecell = Eright – Eleft = EAg+Ag – ECu2+Cu                                        (3.7)
3.2.1 Measurement of Electrode Potential
The potential of individual half-cell cannot be measured.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "We can measure only the difference between the two half-cell potentials that gives the emf of the cell.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "If we arbitrarily choose the potential of one electrode (half-cell) then that of the other can be determined with respect to this.", "fibs": ["electrode"]}
{"text": "According to convention, a half-cell called standard hydrogen electrode (Fig.3.3) represented by Pt(s) H2(g) H+(aq), is assigned a zero potential at all temperatures corresponding to the reaction
H+ (aq) + e– → H2(g)





