{"text": "3.3: Standard Hydrogen Electrode (SHE).", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "The standard hydrogen electrode consists of a platinum electrode coated with platinum black.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "The electrode is dipped in an acidic solution and pure hydrogen gas is bubbled through it.", "fibs": ["electrode"]}
{"text": "The concentration of both the reduced and oxidised forms of hydrogen is maintained at unity (Fig.", "fibs": ["concentration"]}
{"text": "This implies that the pressure of hydrogen gas is one bar and the concentration of hydrogen ion in the solution is one molar.", "fibs": ["pressure"]}
{"text": "At 298 K the emf of the cell, standard hydrogen electrode second half-cell constructed by taking standard hydrogen electrode as anode (reference half-cell) and the other half-cell as cathode, gives the reduction potential of the other half-cell.", "fibs": ["emf"]}
{"text": "If the concentrations of the oxidised and the reduced forms of the species in the right hand half-cell are unity, then the cell potential is equal to standard electrode potential, EƟR of the given half-cell.", "fibs": ["species"]}
{"text": "EƟ = EƟR – EƟL
