{"text": "3.4 Conductance of Electrolytic Solutions
It is necessary to define a few terms before we consider the subject of conductance of electricity through electrolytic solutions.", "fibs": ["subject"]}
{"text": "The electrical resistance is represented by the symbol ‘R’ and it is measured in ohm (Ω) which in terms of SI base units is equal to (kg m2)/(S3 A2).", "fibs": ["resistance"]}
{"text": "It can be measured with the help of a Wheatstone bridge with which you are familiar from your study of physics.", "fibs": ["bridge"]}
{"text": "The electrical resistance of any object is directly proportional to its length, l, and inversely proportional to its area of cross section, A.", "fibs": ["resistance"]}
{"text": "That is,
R ∝  or R = ρ                                                    (3.17)



The constant of proportionality, ρ (Greek, rho), is called resistivity (specific resistance).", "fibs": ["R"]}
{"text": "Its SI units are ohm metre (Ω m) and quite often its submultiple, ohm centimetre (Ω cm) is also used.", "fibs": ["SI"]}
{"text": "IUPAC recommends the use of the term resistivity over specific resistance and hence in the rest of the book we shall use the term resistivity.", "fibs": ["IUPAC"]}
{"text": "Physically, the resistivity for a substance is its resistance when it is one metre long and its area of cross section is one m2.", "fibs": ["resistivity"]}
{"text": "It can be seen that:



1 Ω m = 100 Ω cm or 1 Ω cm = 0.01 Ω m
The inverse of resistance, R, is called conductance, G, and we have the relation:
G = =                                                (3.18)


The SI unit of conductance is siemens, represented by the symbol ‘S’ and is equal to ohm–1 (also known as mho) or Ω–1.", "fibs": ["cm"]}
{"text": "The inverse of resistivity, called conductivity (specific conductance) is represented by the symbol, κ (Greek, kappa).", "fibs": ["resistivity"]}
{"text": "IUPAC has recommended the use of term conductivity over specific conductance and hence we shall use the term conductivity in the rest of the book.", "fibs": ["IUPAC"]}
{"text": "The SI units of conductivity are S m–1 but quite often, κ is expressed in S cm–1.", "fibs": ["SI"]}
{"text": "Conductivity of a material in S m–1 is its conductance when it is 1 m long and its area of cross section is 1 m2.", "fibs": ["Conductivity"]}
{"text": "It may be noted that 1 S cm–1 = 100 S m–1.", "fibs": ["cm–1"]}
{"text": "Table 3.2: The values of Conductivity of some Selected Materials at 298.15 K





It can be seen from Table 3.2 that the magnitude of conductivity varies a great deal and depends on the nature of the material.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "It also depends on the temperature and pressure at which the measurements are made.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "Materials are classified into conductors, insulators and semiconductors depending on the magnitude of their conductivity.", "fibs": ["magnitude"]}
{"text": "Metals and their alloys have very large conductivity and are known as conductors.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "Certain non-metals like carbon-black, graphite and some organic polymers* are also electronically conducting.", "fibs": ["graphite"]}
{"text": "Substances like glass, ceramics, etc., having very low conductivity are known as insulators.", "fibs": ["glass"]}
{"text": "Substances like silicon, doped silicon and gallium arsenide having conductivity between conductors and insulators are called semiconductors and are important electronic materials.", "fibs": ["silicon"]}
{"text": "Certain materials called superconductors by definition have zero resistivity or infinite conductivity.", "fibs": ["definition"]}
{"text": "Earlier, only metals and their alloys at very low temperatures (0 to 15 K) were known to behave as superconductors, but nowadays a number of ceramic materials and mixed oxides are also known to show superconductivity at temperatures as high as 150 K.
Electrical conductance through metals is called metallic or electronic conductance and is due to the movement of electrons.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "The electronic conductance depends on
(i) the nature and structure of the metal
(ii) the number of valence electrons per atom
(iii) temperature (it decreases with increase of temperature).", "fibs": ["conductance"]}
{"text": "* Electronically conducting polymers – In 1977 MacDiarmid, Heeger and Shirakawa discovered that acetylene gas can be polymerised to produce a polymer, polyacetylene when exposed to vapours of iodine acquires metallic lustre and conductivity.", "fibs": ["MacDiarmid"]}
{"text": "Since then several organic conducting polymers have been made such as polyaniline, polypyrrole and polythiophene.", "fibs": ["polyaniline"]}
{"text": "These organic polymers which have properties like metals, being composed wholly of elements like carbon, hydrogen and occasionally nitrogen, oxygen or sulphur, are much lighter than normal metals and can be used for making light-weight batteries.", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "Besides, they have the mechanical properties of polymers such as flexibility so that one can make electronic devices such as transistors that can bend like a sheet of plastic.", "fibs": ["flexibility"]}
{"text": "For the discovery of conducting polymers, MacDiarmid, Heeger and Shirakawa were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for the year 2000.", "fibs": ["discovery"]}
{"text": "As the electrons enter at one end and go out through the other end, the composition of the metallic conductor remains unchanged.", "fibs": ["end"]}
{"text": "The mechanism of conductance through semiconductors is more complex.", "fibs": ["mechanism"]}
{"text": "We already know (Class XI, Unit 7) that even very pure water has small amounts of hydrogen and hydroxyl ions (~10–7M) which lend it very low conductivity (3.5 × 10–5 S m–1).", "fibs": ["XI"]}
{"text": "When electrolytes are dissolved in water, they furnish their own ions in the solution hence its conductivity also increases.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "The conductance of electricity by ions present in the solutions is called electrolytic or ionic conductance.", "fibs": ["conductance"]}
{"text": "The conductivity of electrolytic (ionic) solutions depends on:
(i) the nature of the electrolyte added
(ii) size of the ions produced and their solvation
(iii) the nature of the solvent and its viscosity
(iv) concentration of the electrolyte
(v) temperature (it increases with the increase of temperature).", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "Passage of direct current through ionic solution over a prolonged period can lead to change in its composition due to electrochemical reactions (Section 3.4.1).", "fibs": ["Passage"]}
{"text": "3.4.1 Measurement of the Conductivity of Ionic Solutions
We know that accurate measurement of an unknown resistance can be performed on a Wheatstone bridge.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "However, for measuring the resistance of an ionic solution we face two problems.", "fibs": ["resistance"]}
{"text": "Firstly, passing direct current (DC) changes the composition of the solution.", "fibs": ["DC"]}
{"text": "Secondly, a solution cannot be connected to the bridge like a metallic wire or other solid conductor.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "The first difficulty is resolved by using an alternating current (AC) source of power.", "fibs": ["difficulty"]}
{"text": "The second problem is solved by using a specially designed vessel called conductivity cell.", "fibs": ["problem"]}
{"text": "It is available in several designs and two simple ones are shown in Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
