{"text": "3.4.2 Variation of Conductivity and Molar Conductivity with Concentration
Both conductivity and molar conductivity change with the concentration of the electrolyte.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "Conductivity always decreases with decrease in concentration both, for weak and strong electrolytes.", "fibs": ["Conductivity"]}
{"text": "This can be explained by the fact that the number of ions per unit volume that carry the current in a solution decreases on dilution.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "The conductivity of a solution at any given concentration is the conductance of one unit volume of solution kept between two platinum electrodes with unit area of cross section and at a distance of unit length.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "This is clear from the equation:


 (both A and l are unity in their appropriate units in m or cm)
Molar conductivity of a solution at a given concentration is the conductance of the volume V of solution containing one mole of electrolyte kept between two electrodes with area of cross section A and distance of unit length.", "fibs": ["equation"]}
{"text": "Therefore,

Since l = 1 and A = V ( volume containing 1 mole of electrolyte)
Λm = κ V                                                                                                     (3.22)
Molar conductivity increases with decrease in concentration.", "fibs": ["l"]}
{"text": "This is because the total volume, V, of solution containing one mole of electrolyte also increases.", "fibs": ["volume"]}
{"text": "It has been found that decrease in κ on dilution of a solution is more than compensated by increase in its volume.", "fibs": ["decrease"]}
{"text": "Physically, it means that at a given concentration, Λm can be defined as the conductance of the electrolytic solution kept between the electrodes of a conductivity cell at unit distance but having area of cross section large enough to accommodate sufficient volume of solution that contains one mole of the electrolyte.", "fibs": ["concentration"]}
{"text": "When concentration approaches zero, the molar conductivity is known as limiting molar conductivity and is represented by the symbol Λ°m .", "fibs": ["concentration"]}
