{"text": "3.9 Commonly used mercury cell.", "fibs": ["mercury"]}
{"text": "The reducing agent is zinc and the oxidising agent is mercury (II) oxide.", "fibs": ["agent"]}
{"text": "The overall reaction is represented by
Zn(Hg) + HgO(s) → ZnO(s) + Hg(l)
The cell potential is approximately 1.35 V and remains constant during its life as the overall reaction does not involve any ion in solution whose concentration can change during its life time.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "3.6.2 Secondary Batteries

A secondary cell after use can be recharged by passing current through it in the opposite direction so that it can be used again.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "A good secondary cell can undergo a large number of discharging and charging cycles.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "The most important secondary cell is the lead storage battery (Fig.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "It consists of a lead anode and a grid of lead packed with lead dioxide (PbO2 ) as cathode.", "fibs": ["anode"]}
{"text": "A 38% solution of sulphuric acid is used as an electrolyte.", "fibs": ["solution"]}
{"text": "The cell reactions when the battery is in use are given below:
Anode: Pb(s) + SO42–(aq) → PbSO4(s) + 2e–
Cathode: PbO2(s) + SO42–(aq) + 4H+(aq) + 2e– → PbSO4 (s) + 2H2O (l)
i.e., overall cell reaction consisting of cathode and anode reactions is:

Pb(s) + PbO2(s) + 2H2SO4(aq) → 2PbSO4(s) + 2H2O(l)
On charging the battery the reaction is reversed and PbSO4(s) on anode and cathode is converted into Pb and PbO2, respectively.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "3.10: The Lead storage battery



Fig.", "fibs": ["storage"]}
{"text": "3.11 A rechargeable nickel-cadmium cell in a jelly roll arrangement and separated by a layer soaked in moist sodium or potassium hydroxide.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Another important secondary cell is the nickel-cadmium cell (Fig.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "3.11) which has longer life than the lead storage cell but more expensive to manufacture.", "fibs": ["life"]}
{"text": "We shall not go into details of working of the cell and the electrode reactions during charging and discharging.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "The overall reaction during discharge is:
                

Cd (s) + 2Ni(OH)3 (s) → CdO (s) + 2Ni(OH)2 (s) + H2O (l)
3.7 Fuel Cells
Production of electricity by thermal plants is not a very efficient method and is a major source of pollution.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "In such plants, the chemical energy (heat of combustion) of fossil fuels (coal, gas or oil) is first used for converting water into high pressure steam.", "fibs": ["chemical"]}
{"text": "This is then used to run a turbine to produce electricity.", "fibs": ["turbine"]}
{"text": "We know that a galvanic cell directly converts chemical energy into electricity and is highly efficient.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "It is now possible to make such cells in which reactants are fed continuously to the electrodes and products are removed continuously from the electrolyte compartment.", "fibs": ["electrolyte"]}
{"text": "Galvanic cells that are designed to convert the energy of combustion of fuels like hydrogen, methane, methanol, etc.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "directly into electrical energy are called fuel cells.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "3.12:Fuel cell using H2 and O2 produces electricity.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "One of the most successful fuel cells uses the reaction of hydrogen with oxygen to form water (Fig.", "fibs": ["fuel"]}
{"text": "The cell was used for providing electrical power in the Apollo space programme.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "The water vapours produced during the reaction were condensed and added to the drinking water supply for the astronauts.", "fibs": ["water"]}
{"text": "In the cell, hydrogen and oxygen are bubbled through porous carbon electrodes into concentrated aqueous sodium hydroxide solution.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Catalysts like finely divided platinum or palladium metal are incorporated into the electrodes for increasing the rate of electrode reactions.", "fibs": ["platinum"]}
{"text": "The electrode reactions are given below:
Cathode: O2(g) + 2H2O(l) + 4e–→ 4OH–(aq)
Anode: 2H2 (g) + 4OH–(aq) → 4H2O(l) + 4e–
Overall reaction being:
2H2(g) + O2(g) → 2H2O(l)

The cell runs continuously as long as the reactants are supplied.", "fibs": ["electrode"]}
{"text": "Fuel cells produce electricity with an efficiency of about 70 % compared to thermal plants whose efficiency is about 40%.", "fibs": ["electricity"]}
{"text": "There has been tremendous progress in the development of new electrode materials, better catalysts and electrolytes for increasing the efficiency of fuel cells.", "fibs": ["progress"]}
{"text": "These have been used in automobiles on an experimental basis.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "Fuel cells are pollution free and in view of their future importance, a variety of fuel cells have been fabricated and tried.", "fibs": ["pollution"]}
{"text": "3.8 Corrosion

                Corrosion slowly coats the surfaces of metallic objects with oxides or other salts of the metal.", "fibs": ["Corrosion"]}
{"text": "The rusting of iron, tarnishing of silver, development of green coating on copper and bronze are some of the examples of corrosion.", "fibs": ["iron"]}
{"text": "It causes enormous damage to buildings, bridges, ships and to all objects made of metals especially that of iron.", "fibs": ["damage"]}
{"text": "We lose crores of rupees every year on account of corrosion.", "fibs": ["year"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "3.13: Corrosion of iron in atmosphere

In corrosion, a metal is oxidised by loss of electrons to oxygen and formation of oxides.", "fibs": ["iron"]}
{"text": "Corrosion of iron (commonly known as rusting) occurs in presence of water and air.", "fibs": ["Corrosion"]}
{"text": "The chemistry of corrosion is quite complex but it may be considered essentially as an electrochemical phenomenon.", "fibs": ["chemistry"]}
{"text": "At a particular spot (Fig.", "fibs": ["spot"]}
{"text": "3.13) of an object made of iron, oxidation takes place and that spot behaves as anode and we can write the reaction
Anode: 2 Fe (s) → 2 Fe2+ + 4 e–               
Electrons released at anodic spot move through the metal and go to another spot on the metal and reduce oxygen in the presence of H+ (which is believed to be available from H2CO3 formed due to dissolution of carbon dioxide from air into water.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen ion in water may also be available due to dissolution of other acidic oxides from the atmosphere).", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "This spot behaves as cathode with the reaction
Cathode: O2(g) + 4 H+(aq) + 4 e– → 2 H2O (l)     
The overall reaction being:
2Fe(s) + O2(g) + 4H+(aq) → 2Fe2 +(aq) + 2 H2O (l)        EƟ(cell)=1.67 V

The ferrous ions are further oxidised by atmospheric oxygen to ferric ions which come out as rust in the form of hydrated ferric oxide (Fe2O3.", "fibs": ["spot"]}
{"text": "x H2O) and with further production of hydrogen ions.", "fibs": ["x"]}
{"text": "Prevention of corrosion is of prime importance.", "fibs": ["corrosion"]}
{"text": "It not only saves money but also helps in preventing accidents such as a bridge collapse or failure of a key component due to corrosion.", "fibs": ["money"]}
{"text": "One of the simplest methods of preventing corrosion is to prevent the surface of the metallic object to come in contact with atmosphere.", "fibs": ["corrosion"]}
{"text": "This can be done by covering the surface with paint or by some chemicals (e.g.", "fibs": ["surface"]}
{"text": "bisphenol).", "fibs": ["bisphenol"]}
{"text": "Another simple method is to cover the surface by other metals (Sn, Zn, etc.)", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "that are inert or react to save the object.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "An electrochemical method is to provide a sacrificial electrode of another metal (like Mg, Zn, etc.)", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "which corrodes itself but saves the object.", "fibs": ["object"]}
