{"text": "The Hydrogen Economy
At present the main source of energy that is driving our economy is fossil fuels such as coal, oil and gas.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "As more people on the planet aspire to improve their standard of living, their energy requirement will increase.", "fibs": ["planet"]}
{"text": "In fact, the per capita consumption of energy used is a measure of development.", "fibs": ["fact"]}
{"text": "Of course, it is assumed that energy is used for productive purpose and not merely wasted.", "fibs": ["course"]}
{"text": "We are already aware that carbon dioxide produced by the combustion of fossil fuels is resulting in the ‘Greenhouse Effect’.", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "This is leading to a rise in the temperature of the Earth’s surface, causing polar ice to melt and ocean levels to rise.", "fibs": ["rise"]}
{"text": "This will flood low-lying areas along the coast and some island nations such as Maldives face total submergence.", "fibs": ["flood"]}
{"text": "In order to avoid such a catastrope, we need to limit our use of carbonaceous fuels.", "fibs": ["order"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen provides an ideal alternative as its combustion results in water only.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen production must come from splitting water using solar energy.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "Therefore, hydrogen can be used as a renewable and non polluting source of energy.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "This is the vision of the Hydrogen Economy.", "fibs": ["vision"]}
{"text": "Both the production of hydrogen by electrolysis of water and hydrogen combustion in a fuel cell will be important in the future.", "fibs": ["production"]}
{"text": "Summary
An electrochemical cell consists of two metallic electrodes dipping in electrolytic solution(s).", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "Thus an important component of the electrochemical cell is the ionic conductor or electrolyte.", "fibs": ["component"]}
{"text": "In galvanic cell, thechemical energy of a spontaneous redox reaction is converted into electrical work, whereas in an electrolytic cell, electrical energy is used to carry out a non-spontaneous redox reaction.", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "The standard electrode potential for any electrode dipping in an appropriate solution is defined with respect to standard electrode potential of hydrogen electrode taken as zero.", "fibs": ["electrode"]}
{"text": "The standard potential of the cell can be obtained by taking the difference of the standard potentials of cathode and anode (EƟ(cell)= EƟcathode – EƟanode).", "fibs": ["cell"]}
{"text": "The standard potential of the cells are related to standard Gibbs energy (∆rGƟ = –nFEƟ(cell)) and equilibrium constant(∆rGƟ = – RT ln K) of the reaction taking place in the cell.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "Concentration dependence of the potentials of the electrodes and the cells are given by Nernst equation.", "fibs": ["Concentration"]}
{"text": "The conductivity, κ, of an electrolytic solution depends on the concentration of the electrolyte, nature of solvent and temperature.", "fibs": ["conductivity"]}
{"text": "Molar conductivity, Λm, is defined by = κ/c where c is the concentration.", "fibs": ["Molar"]}
{"text": "Conductivity decreases but molar conductivity increases with decrease in concentration.", "fibs": ["Conductivity"]}
{"text": "It increases slowly with decrease in concentration for strong electrolytes while the increase is very steep for weak electrolytes in very dilute solutions.", "fibs": ["decrease"]}
{"text": "Kohlrausch found that molar conductivity at infinite dilution, for an electrolyte is sum of the contribution of the molar conductivity of the ions in which it dissociates.", "fibs": ["molar"]}
{"text": "It is known as law of independent migration of ions and has many applications.", "fibs": ["law"]}
{"text": "Ions conduct electricity through the solution but oxidation and reduction of the ions take place at the electrodes in an electrochemical cell.", "fibs": ["conduct"]}
{"text": "Batteries and fuel cells are very useful forms of galvanic cell.", "fibs": ["fuel"]}
{"text": "Corrosion of metals is essentially an electrochemical phenomenon.", "fibs": ["Corrosion"]}
{"text": "Electrochemical principles are relevant to the Hydrogen Economy.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
